{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645243"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:14:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:14:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18097"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18097"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.9,0.1,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10811"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96541"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10590"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25174"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary source of progesterone during the third trimester of pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Placenta","Corpus luteum","Maternal ovaries","Maternal adrenal glands","Fetal adrenal glands"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eplacenta\u003C/strong\u003E is the main source of progesterone during the third trimester of pregnancy. While the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorpus luteum\u003C/strong\u003E produces progesterone in early pregnancy, the placenta takes over as the primary source between 8-12 weeks gestation. Progesterone production continues to increase throughout pregnancy, with the highest levels occurring in the third trimester.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ematernal ovaries\u003C/strong\u003E produce progesterone during the menstrual cycle, but their contribution during pregnancy is minimal. \u003Cstrong\u003EFetal adrenal glands\u003C/strong\u003E primarily produce precursors for oestrogen synthesis but not significant amounts of progesterone. \u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal adrenal glands\u003C/strong\u003E produce only small amounts of progesterone compared to the placenta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlacental progesterone is essential for maintaining pregnancy by promoting endometrial secretory changes, suppressing uterine contractions, and supporting maternal immune tolerance of the fetus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Progesterone supports pregnancy by stimulating secretory changes in the endometrium and inhibiting uterine contractions.","The corpus luteum produces progesterone until the placenta takes over production at around 8-12 weeks gestation.","Progesterone levels rise throughout pregnancy, reaching peak levels in the third trimester."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 83; pg. 1050"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96541"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18097"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic